The registry CRUD verbs operate on `~/.rackabel/registry.toml` and never touch Live,
the host, or the socket — so they are deterministic on any machine (DESIGN §3.2, the
SuperCollider "operable with a dead daemon" lesson). RACKABEL_HOME is pinned to a
sandbox per case; project paths are absolute temp dirs, matched with `[..]`.

Register the bundled fixture project (its dir basename becomes the entry name):

```
$ rackabel dev register my-ext
[✓] registered my-ext

```

List shows one enabled row (STATUS / NAME / PATH):

```
$ rackabel dev list
[✓] my-ext  enabled   [..]/my-ext

```

`--json` emits the stable machine shape (sorted keys):

```
$ rackabel dev list --json
{
  "extensions": [
    {
      "enabled": true,
      "name": "my-ext",
      "path": "[..]/my-ext",
      "status": "enabled"
    }
  ]
}

```

Disable flips the one `enabled` flag; the row shows `disabled` and a `[!]`:

```
$ rackabel dev disable my-ext
[✓] disabled my-ext
    help: run `rackabel dev reload` to drop it from a running host

```

```
$ rackabel dev list
[!] my-ext  disabled  [..]/my-ext

```

Enable flips it back:

```
$ rackabel dev enable my-ext
[✓] enabled my-ext
    help: run `rackabel dev reload` to load it into a running host

```

Unregister removes it; the registry is then empty:

```
$ rackabel dev unregister my-ext
[✓] unregistered my-ext

```

```
$ rackabel dev list
    help: no extensions registered — `rackabel dev register [PATH]` to add one

```

Unregistering something that was never there names the bad target (exit 3, RK0309):

```
$ rackabel dev unregister nope
? 3
error: no registry entry named or at `nope` [RK0309]
  --> nope
  help: run `rackabel dev list` to see registered extensions
(run `rackabel explain RK0309` for details)

```
